Steps to Allow FTP Directory Access via SELinux
Verify SELinux Context on the Directory Check the current SELinux label:

ls -Z /path/to/directory
If itâ€™s incorrect, you can set an appropriate FTP label.

Apply the Correct SELinux Context Use semanage to allow FTP users to access the directory:

sudo semanage fcontext -a -t public_content_t "/path/to/directory(/.*)?"
This command ensures that SELinux treats the directory as accessible by FTP.

Relabel the Directory Apply the new SELinux label:

sudo restorecon -R /path/to/directory


Verify Current SELinux Labels
Run:

ls -Z /var/ftp/pub
This will show the specific labels for the pub directory and its files.

2. Correct Unlabeled Files
For the directory that is unlabeled_t, restore its default SELinux context:

sudo restorecon -R /var/ftp/pub
This should apply the appropriate SELinux policies based on the default file context.

3. Fix Incorrect Labels (cert_t)
If the cert_t label isn't appropriate, you can manually set the directory to public_content_t:
sudo semanage fcontext -a -t public_content_t "/var/ftp/pub(/.*)?"

Then apply the changes:

sudo restorecon -R /var/ftp/pub
